        <title environment="title" chapter_type="Week" wbtag="title" scope="section" course="Math 1010" chapter="8" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" serial="8.1" slide="">
Absolute/Relative (Global/Local) Extrema
</title>
        <slides environment="" chapter_type="">
          <slide environment="" chapter_type="Week" id="s3" slide="3" course="Math 1010" chapter="8" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" chapter_title="" section_title=" AbsoluteRelative GlobalLocal Extrema "><keywords slide="3" environ="slide" chapter="8" course="Math 1010"><keyword chapter="8" slide="3">absolute minimum</keyword><keyword chapter="8" slide="3">global minimum</keyword><keyword chapter="8" slide="3">absolute maximum</keyword><keyword chapter="8" slide="3">global maximum</keyword><keyword chapter="8" slide="3">minimum</keyword><keyword chapter="8" slide="3">maximum</keyword><keyword chapter="8" slide="3">local/relative minimum</keyword><keyword chapter="8" slide="3">local/relative maximum</keyword></keywords>
<title environment="title" chapter_type="Week" wbtag="title" scope="section" course="Math 1010" chapter="8" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" serial="" slide="3">
Absolute/Relative (Global/Local) Extrema
</title>
Consider a function $f : A \longrightarrow\mathbb{R}$.
<hc_keyword course="Math 1010" chapter="8" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="hc_keyword" class="hidden">absolute minimum</hc_keyword><hc_keyword course="Math 1010" chapter="8" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="hc_keyword" class="hidden">global minimum</hc_keyword><hc_keyword course="Math 1010" chapter="8" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="hc_keyword" class="hidden">absolute maximum</hc_keyword><hc_keyword course="Math 1010" chapter="8" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="hc_keyword" class="hidden">global maximum</hc_keyword><statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Definition" wbtag="defn" num="1" md5="45f15ba1d0f36ef5c82821a270271117" course="Math 1010" chapter="8" slide="3" item="8.1">
<xh:ul xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="statement">
<xh:li environment="statement">
If there is an element $c \in A$ such that: $f(c) \leq f(x)$
for all $x \in A$, we say that $f(c)$ is the (global/absolute) <xh:b environment="statement">minimum</xh:b> of $f$.


</xh:li>
<xh:li environment="statement">
If there is an element $d \in A$ such that: $f(d) \geq f(x)$
for all $x \in A$, we say that $f(d)$ is the (global/absolute) <xh:b environment="statement">maximum</xh:b> of $f$.


</xh:li></xh:ul>
</statement>
<statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Definition" wbtag="defn" num="2" md5="7218158ad5abe45b65652acc7a1e40eb" course="Math 1010" chapter="8" slide="3" item="8.2">
<newcol course="Math 1010" chapter="8" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="newcol">
<xh:ul xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="newcol">
<xh:li environment="newcol">
If $f(c) \leq f(x)$ for all $x$ in an open interval containing $c$,
we say that $f$ has a <xh:b environment="newcol">local/relative minimum</xh:b> at $c$.
</xh:li>
<xh:li environment="newcol">
If $f(c) \geq f(x)$ for all $x$ in an open interval containing $c$,
we say that $f$ has a <xh:b environment="newcol">local/relative maximum</xh:b> at $c$.
</xh:li>
</xh:ul>
</newcol>
</statement>
<newcol course="Math 1010" chapter="8" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="newcol">
<xh:div xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" class="image" environment="newcol">
<xh:a href="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Extrema_example_original.svg#/media/File:Extrema_example_original.svg" environment="newcol"><xh:img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/1/1e/Extrema_example.svg" alt="Extrema example original.svg" environment="newcol"/></xh:a><xh:br environment="newcol"/>By KSmrq - <xh:a class="external free" href="http://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Extrema_example.svg" environment="newcol">http://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Extrema_example.svg</xh:a>, <xh:a href="http://www.gnu.org/licenses/old-licenses/fdl-1.2.html" title="GNU Free Documentation License 1.2" environment="newcol">GFDL 1.2</xh:a>, <xh:a href="https://commons.wikimedia.org/w/index.php?curid=6870865" environment="newcol">Link</xh:a>
</xh:div>
</newcol>
</slide>
          <slide environment="" chapter_type="Week" wbtag="slide" id="s4" slide="4" course="Math 1010" chapter="8" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" chapter_title="" section_title=" AbsoluteRelative GlobalLocal Extrema "><keywords slide="4" environ="slide" chapter="8" course="Math 1010"><keyword chapter="8" slide="4">First Derivative Test</keyword></keywords>
<statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Theorem" wbtag="thm" num="3" title="First Derivative Test" md5="32c20d25b656b81930a8a63bc1b06476" course="Math 1010" chapter="8" slide="4" item="8.3"><label course="Math 1010" chapter="8" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="statement" wbtag="label" name="thm:fdt" type="Theorem"/>

<title environment="title" chapter_type="Week" wbtag="statement" scope="" course="Math 1010" chapter="8" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" serial="" slide="4">First Derivative Test</title>
Let $f : A \longrightarrow\mathbb{R} $ be a continuous function.
For $c \in A$, if there exists an open interval $(a, b)$ containing $c$
such that $f'(x) &lt; 0$ (in particular it exists) for all $x \in (a, c)$,
and $f'(x) &gt; 0$ for all $x \in (c, b)$, then $f$ has a local minimum at $c$.
<xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" wbtag="newline" environment="statement"/>
Similarly, if $f'(x) &gt; 0$ for all $x \in (a, c)$ and $f'(x) &lt; 0 $ for
all $x \in (c, b)$, then $f$ has a local maximum at $c$.
</statement>
<xh:strong xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="">Note:</xh:strong>
<newcol course="Math 1010" chapter="8" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="newcol">
In the special case that the domain of $f$ is an open interval $(a, b)$,
if $f'(x) &gt; 0$ for <xh:u xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="newcol">all</xh:u> $x \in (a, c)$, and $f'(x) &lt; 0$ for <xh:u xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="newcol">all</xh:u>
$x \in (c, b)$,
then $f$ has an absolute maximum at $c$.
<xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="newcol"/>Similarly $f$ has an absolute minimum at $c$
if each of the above inequalities is reversed.
</newcol>
<statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Example" wbtag="eg" num="4" md5="7c80e8e3f96891c595d6e3c37af5a5b3" course="Math 1010" chapter="8" slide="4" item="8.4">
<col_ul course="Math 1010" chapter="8" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="col_ul" wbtag="col_ul">
<col_li course="Math 1010" chapter="8" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="col_ul" wbtag="col_li">
In <ref environment="col_ul" chapter_type="" label="dbee36c80786eacbe8adcb4d1cbb5875" name="" wbtag="ref" course="Math 1010" chapter="8" slide="4" src-course="Math 1010" src-chapter="7" src-slide="9" type="Example" item="7.6" src-filename="week7.xml" md5="dbee36c80786eacbe8adcb4d1cbb5875" class="knowl" serial=""><title>Example 7.6</title></ref>,
the function has a local maximum at $x = -5$, and a local minimum at $x = 1$.
</col_li><col_li course="Math 1010" chapter="8" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="col_ul" wbtag="col_li">
In <ref environment="col_ul" chapter_type="" label="5f48bed597bacc500b121063710fd810" name="" wbtag="ref" course="Math 1010" chapter="8" slide="4" src-course="Math 1010" src-chapter="7" src-slide="10" type="Example" item="7.7" src-filename="week7.xml" md5="5f48bed597bacc500b121063710fd810" class="knowl" serial=""><title>Example 7.7</title></ref>,
the function has only one local extremum, namely a local minimum at $x = -1$.
In fact, $f(-1) = 0$ is the absolute minimum of $f$.
</col_li></col_ul>
</statement>
</slide>
          <slide environment="" chapter_type="Week" wbtag="slide" id="s5" slide="5" course="Math 1010" chapter="8" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" chapter_title="" section_title=" AbsoluteRelative GlobalLocal Extrema "><keywords slide="5" environ="slide" chapter="8" course="Math 1010"/>
<statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Exercise" wbtag="ex" num="5" md5="db5b8dd25718de0b51bbe5f4200151e3" course="Math 1010" chapter="8" slide="5" item="8.5">
$\displaystyle f(x)=x^{\frac{1}{3}}-\frac{1}{3}x-\frac{2}{3}$ for $x&gt;0$. Show that $f(x)\leq 0$ for all $x&gt;0$.  Then, deduce that:
\[
u^{\frac{1}{3}}v^{\frac{2}{3}} \leq \frac{1}{3}u + \frac{2}{3}v
\]
for $u$, $v&gt;0$.
</statement>
</slide>
