          <slide environment="" chapter_type="Week" wbtag="slide" id="s7" slide="7" course="Math 1010" chapter="8" section="2" subsection="" subsubsection="" chapter_title="" section_title=" WeBWorK "><keywords slide="7" environ="slide" chapter="8" course="Math 1010"><keyword chapter="8" slide="7">Second Derivative Test</keyword></keywords>
<statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Theorem" wbtag="thm" num="6" title="Second Derivative Test" md5="5b5638f2b35a91cfb0919861ec06d0b2" course="Math 1010" chapter="8" slide="7" item="8.6"><label course="Math 1010" chapter="8" chapter_type="" section="2" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="statement" wbtag="label" name="thm:sdt" type="Theorem"/>

<title environment="title" chapter_type="Week" wbtag="statement" scope="" course="Math 1010" chapter="8" section="2" subsection="" subsubsection="" serial="" slide="7">Second Derivative Test</title>
Let $f$ be a function twice differentiable at $c \in \mathbb{R}$,
such that $f'(c) = 0$.  If:
<xh:ul xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="statement">
<xh:li environment="statement">$f''(c) &gt; 0$, then $f$ has a local minimum at $c$.
</xh:li>
<xh:li environment="statement">$f''(c) &lt; 0$, then $f$ has a local maximum at $c$.
</xh:li></xh:ul>
</statement>
<substatement environment="substatement" chapter_type="Week" type="Proof" wbtag="proof" md5="761dad2fa60bbf695fca24c4e8bb33fa" course="Math 1010" chapter="8" slide="7" of="5b5638f2b35a91cfb0919861ec06d0b2">
<newcol course="Math 1010" chapter="8" chapter_type="" section="2" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="newcol">
<xh:strong xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="newcol">Sketch of Proof.</xh:strong>
Suppose $f''(c) &gt; 0$, by the definition of $f''(c)$ as the derivative of $f'$ at $c$,
we have:
\[
0 &lt; f''(c) = \lim_{h \rightarrow 0}\frac{f'(c + h)  - f'(c)}{h}
= \lim_{h \rightarrow 0}\frac{f'(c + h)}{h}\;.
\]
It follows from the above identity that $f'(c + h)$ is $&gt; 0$ for sufficiently small
positive $h$, and $&lt; 0$ for sufficiently small negative $h$.
<xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="newcol"/>
<collapse course="Math 1010" chapter="8" chapter_type="" section="2" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="collapse">
Hence there is an open interval $(a, b)$ containing $c$ such that $f'$ is negative on
$(a, c)$ and positive on $(c, b)$.  So, $f$ has a local minimum at $c$ by the First Derivative Test.
<xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="newcol"/>
<collapse course="Math 1010" chapter="8" chapter_type="" section="2" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="collapse">
The case $f''(c) &lt; 0$ may be proved similarly.
<qed course="Math 1010" chapter="8" chapter_type="" section="2" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol"/>
</collapse></collapse></newcol>
</substatement>
</slide>
          <slide environment="" chapter_type="Week" wbtag="slide" id="s8" slide="8" course="Math 1010" chapter="8" section="2" subsection="" subsubsection="" chapter_title="" section_title=" WeBWorK "><keywords slide="8" environ="slide" chapter="8" course="Math 1010"/>
<statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Example" wbtag="eg" num="7" md5="10a13b53c940ec6ea198fc83858728f7" course="Math 1010" chapter="8" slide="8" item="8.7">
Consider the function $f(x) = x^3 + 6x^2  - 15x + 7$ in
<ref environment="statement" chapter_type="" label="dbee36c80786eacbe8adcb4d1cbb5875" name="" wbtag="ref" course="Math 1010" chapter="8" slide="8" src-course="Math 1010" src-chapter="7" src-slide="9" type="Example" item="7.6" src-filename="week7.xml" md5="dbee36c80786eacbe8adcb4d1cbb5875" class="knowl" serial=""><title>Example 7.6</title></ref>, we have:
<xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" wbtag="newline" environment="statement"/>
<newcol course="Math 1010" chapter="8" chapter_type="" section="2" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="newcol">
\[
f''(x) = 6x + 12
\]
<collapse course="Math 1010" chapter="8" chapter_type="" section="2" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="collapse">
The function $f$ has a two stationary points $c = -5, 1$
where $f'(c) = 0$.
<xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" wbtag="newline" environment="newcol"/>
<collapse course="Math 1010" chapter="8" chapter_type="" section="2" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="collapse">
Since:
\[
f''(-5) = -18,\quad f''(1) = 18,
\]
<collapse course="Math 1010" chapter="8" chapter_type="" section="2" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="collapse">
by the <ref environment="newcol" chapter_type="" label="thm:sdt" name="" wbtag="ref" course="Math 1010" chapter="8" slide="8" src-course="Math 1010" src-chapter="8" src-slide="7" type="Theorem" item="8.6" src-filename="week8.xml" md5="5b5638f2b35a91cfb0919861ec06d0b2" class="knowl" serial=""><title>Second Derivative Test</title></ref> $f(-5)$ is a local maximum,
and $f(1)$ is a local minimum.  (This corroborates the conclusions
of the <ref environment="newcol" chapter_type="" label="thm:fdt" name="" wbtag="ref" course="Math 1010" chapter="8" slide="8" src-course="Math 1010" src-chapter="8" src-slide="4" type="Theorem" item="8.3" src-filename="week8.xml" md5="32c20d25b656b81930a8a63bc1b06476" class="knowl" serial=""><title>First Derivative Test</title></ref> applied to the same function, see <ref environment="newcol" chapter_type="" label="7c80e8e3f96891c595d6e3c37af5a5b3" name="" wbtag="ref" course="Math 1010" chapter="8" slide="8" src-course="Math 1010" src-chapter="8" src-slide="4" type="Example" item="8.4" src-filename="week8.xml" md5="7c80e8e3f96891c595d6e3c37af5a5b3" class="knowl" serial=""><title>Example 8.4</title></ref>.)
</collapse></collapse></collapse></newcol></statement>
<statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Example" wbtag="eg" num="8" md5="f56a0d628879ee342067f8b08b106671" course="Math 1010" chapter="8" slide="8" item="8.8">
<newcol course="Math 1010" chapter="8" chapter_type="" section="2" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="newcol">
Consider $g(x) = x^4$.  Then, $g'(x) = 4x^3$, which implies that
$c = 0$ is the only point where $g'(c) = 0$.
<xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" wbtag="newline" environment="newcol"/>
<collapse course="Math 1010" chapter="8" chapter_type="" section="2" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="collapse">
The second derivative of $g$ is $g''(x) = 12x^2$.  Hence, $g''(c) = g''(0) = 0$.
<xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" wbtag="newline" environment="newcol"/>
<collapse course="Math 1010" chapter="8" chapter_type="" section="2" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="collapse">
In this case, no conclusion can be drawn from the <ref environment="newcol" chapter_type="" label="thm:sdt" name="" wbtag="ref" course="Math 1010" chapter="8" slide="8" src-course="Math 1010" src-chapter="8" src-slide="7" type="Theorem" item="8.6" src-filename="week8.xml" md5="5b5638f2b35a91cfb0919861ec06d0b2" class="knowl" serial=""><title>Second Derivative Test</title></ref>,
regarding whether $g(0)$ is a local minimum, maximum, or neither.
<xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" wbtag="newline" environment="newcol"/>
<collapse course="Math 1010" chapter="8" chapter_type="" section="2" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="collapse">
However, one can still apply the <ref environment="newcol" chapter_type="" label="thm:fdt" name="" wbtag="ref" course="Math 1010" chapter="8" slide="8" src-course="Math 1010" src-chapter="8" src-slide="4" type="Theorem" item="8.3" src-filename="week8.xml" md5="32c20d25b656b81930a8a63bc1b06476" class="knowl" serial=""><title>First Derivative Test</title></ref> to conclude that 
$f(0) = 0$ is a local minimum.
</collapse></collapse></collapse></newcol></statement>
