      <section environment="" chapter_type="" type="Section" wbtag="section" title=" Concavity " course="Math 1010" chapter="8" num="3" serial="8.3">
        <title environment="title" chapter_type="Week" wbtag="title" scope="section" course="Math 1010" chapter="8" section="3" subsection="" subsubsection="" serial="8.3" slide="">
Concavity
</title>
        <slides environment="" chapter_type="">
          <slide environment="" chapter_type="Week" id="s9" slide="9" course="Math 1010" chapter="8" section="3" subsection="" subsubsection="" chapter_title="" section_title=" Concavity "><keywords slide="9" environ="slide" chapter="8" course="Math 1010"><keyword chapter="8" slide="9">concave up</keyword><keyword chapter="8" slide="9">concave down</keyword><keyword chapter="8" slide="9">inflection point</keyword></keywords>
<title environment="title" chapter_type="Week" wbtag="title" scope="section" course="Math 1010" chapter="8" section="3" subsection="" subsubsection="" serial="" slide="9">
Concavity
</title>
Let $f$ be a twice differentiable function.
If $f''$ is positive (negative)
on an open interval $(a, b)$, then the graph of $f$ over $(a, b)$
is <xh:b xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="">concave up</xh:b> (resp. <xh:strong xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="">down</xh:strong><hc_keyword course="Math 1010" chapter="8" chapter_type="" section="3" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="hc_keyword" class="hidden">concave down</hc_keyword>  ).
<xh:p xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment=""/>
<newcol course="Math 1010" chapter="8" chapter_type="" section="3" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="newcol">
This is due to the fact that $f''$ being positive (resp. negative) corresponds to
$f'$ being increasing (resp. decreasing).
<xh:p xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="newcol"/>
<collapse course="Math 1010" chapter="8" chapter_type="" section="3" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="collapse">
<xh:div xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" class="image" environment="newcol">
<xh:a href="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Animated_illustration_of_inflection_point.gif#/media/File:Animated_illustration_of_inflection_point.gif" environment="newcol"><xh:img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/7/78/Animated_illustration_of_inflection_point.gif" alt="Animated illustration of inflection point.gif" environment="newcol"/></xh:a><xh:br environment="newcol"/>By dino - <xh:a class="external free" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Animated_illustration_of_inflection_point.gif" environment="newcol">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Animated_illustration_of_inflection_point.gif</xh:a>Public Domain, <xh:a href="https://commons.wikimedia.org/w/index.php?curid=9704293" environment="newcol">Link</xh:a>
</xh:div>
<collapse course="Math 1010" chapter="8" chapter_type="" section="3" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="collapse">
A point on the graph of $f$ where the concavity changes is called an
<xh:b xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="newcol">inflection point</xh:b>.
It corresponds to a point in the domain of $f$ where $f''$ changes sign.
</collapse></collapse></newcol>
</slide>
          <slide environment="" chapter_type="Week" wbtag="slide" id="s10" slide="10" course="Math 1010" chapter="8" section="3" subsection="" subsubsection="" chapter_title="" section_title=" Concavity "><keywords slide="10" environ="slide" chapter="8" course="Math 1010"/>
<statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Example" wbtag="eg" num="9" md5="5a3a60d551482778c53e979de980d97e" course="Math 1010" chapter="8" slide="10" item="8.9">
Sketch the graph of:
\[
f(x) = \dfrac{x^2 + x - 2}{x^2}
\]
by first finding the following information about $f$:
<xh:ol xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="statement">
<xh:li environment="statement"> Domain.
<newcol course="Math 1010" chapter="8" chapter_type="" section="3" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="newcol">
\[
\{x \in \mathbb{R} : x \neq 0 \} = (-\infty, 0 ) \cup (0, \infty)
\]
<xh:hr environment="newcol"/>
</newcol>
</xh:li>
<xh:li environment="statement"> $x$-intercepts (if sufficiently easy to find), and $y$-intercept.
<newcol course="Math 1010" chapter="8" chapter_type="" section="3" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="newcol">
$f(x) = 0$ if and only if $x \neq 0$
and $x^2 + x - 2 = (x - 1)(x + 2) = 0$.
Hence, the $x$-intercepts are:
\[
x = 1, -2.
\]
In general, the $y$-intercept of the graph of a function
is the value of the function at $x = 0$.
In this case, $0$ is not in the domain of $f$,
hence the graph of $f$ has no $y$-intercept.
<xh:hr environment="newcol"/>
</newcol>
</xh:li>
<xh:li environment="statement">
Asymptotes (Horizontal, Vertical, Oblique)
<newcol course="Math 1010" chapter="8" chapter_type="" section="3" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="newcol">
\[
\lim_{x \rightarrow \infty} f(x) = \lim_{x \rightarrow -\infty} f(x) = 1.
\]
Hence, the graph of $f$ has one horizontal asymptote: $y = 1$.
<xh:p environment="newcol"/>
The value $f(x)$ is defined for all $x \neq 0$.
<xh:p environment="newcol"/>
<collapse course="Math 1010" chapter="8" chapter_type="" section="3" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="collapse">
Near $x = 0$, we have:
\[
\lim_{x \rightarrow 0^-} f(x) = \lim_{x \rightarrow 0^+} f(x) = -\infty.
\]
Hence, the graph of $f$ has a vertical asymptote at $x = 0$.
<xh:p environment="newcol"/>
<collapse course="Math 1010" chapter="8" chapter_type="" section="3" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="collapse">
Since $f(x)$ approaches $1$ as $x$ approaches $\pm \infty$,
the graph of $f$ has no oblique asymptote.
<xh:hr environment="newcol"/>
</collapse></collapse></newcol>
</xh:li>
<xh:li environment="statement">
	Intervals where $f$ is increasing/decreasing.
	
<newcol course="Math 1010" chapter="8" chapter_type="" section="3" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="newcol">
	\[
	\begin{split}
	f'(x) &amp;= \frac{x^2(2x + 1) - (x^2 + x - 2)2x}{\left(x^2\right)^2}\\
	&amp;= \frac{x^2(2x + 1) - (x^2 + x - 2)2x}{\left(x^2\right)^2}\\
	&amp;= \frac{1}{x^{3}} \left(4 - x\right)
	\end{split}
	\]
	Hence, the points $c$ where $f'$ possibly changes sign are $c = 0, 4$.
	<xh:p environment="newcol"/>
	  
<collapse course="Math 1010" chapter="8" chapter_type="" section="3" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="collapse">
	  <xh:table class="table-hover table table-striped table-bordered" style="text-align:center" environment="newcol">
	    <xh:tr environment="newcol">
	      <xh:td environment="newcol">$y = f(x)$:</xh:td><xh:td environment="newcol"><xh:strong environment="newcol">$\searrow$</xh:strong></xh:td><xh:td environment="newcol"><xh:strong environment="newcol">$\nearrow$</xh:strong></xh:td><xh:td environment="newcol"><xh:strong environment="newcol">$\searrow$</xh:strong></xh:td>
	    </xh:tr>
	    <xh:tr environment="newcol">
	      <xh:td environment="newcol">$f'(x)$:</xh:td>
	      <xh:td environment="newcol">$-$</xh:td><xh:td environment="newcol">$+$</xh:td><xh:td environment="newcol">$-$</xh:td>
	    </xh:tr>
	    <xh:tr environment="newcol">
	      <xh:td environment="newcol">$x$:</xh:td><xh:td environment="newcol">$(-\infty, 0)$</xh:td><xh:td environment="newcol">$(0, 4)$</xh:td><xh:td environment="newcol">$(4, \infty)$</xh:td>
	    </xh:tr>
	  </xh:table>
	  It follows from the sign chart that $f$ is increasing on $(0, 4]$,
	  and decreasing on $(-\infty, 0)$ and $[4, \infty)$.
	  
<xh:hr environment="newcol"/>
	  
</collapse></newcol>
	  </xh:li>
<xh:li environment="statement">
	    "Turning Points" on the graph of $f$ (i.e. points corresponding to local extrema).
	    
<newcol course="Math 1010" chapter="8" chapter_type="" section="3" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="newcol">
	    It follows from the sign chart above that $f$ as a local maximum at $x = 4$.
	    The corresponding point on the graph is $(4, f(4)) = (4, 9/8)$.
	    
<xh:hr environment="newcol"/>
	    
</newcol>
	  </xh:li>
<xh:li environment="statement">
	    Intervals where $f$ is concave up/down.
	    
<newcol course="Math 1010" chapter="8" chapter_type="" section="3" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="newcol">
	    The second derivative of $f$ is:
	    \[
	    f''(x) = \frac{1}{x^{4}} \left(2 x - 12\right)
	    \]
	    The points where $f''$ possibly changes sign are points $p$ where $f''(p) = 0$,
	    or where $f''(p)$ is undefined.
	    In this case, there are two such point: $p = 0, 6$.
	    <xh:p environment="newcol"/>
	      
<collapse course="Math 1010" chapter="8" chapter_type="" section="3" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="collapse">
	      <xh:table class="table-hover table table-striped table-bordered" style="text-align:center" environment="newcol">
		<xh:tr environment="newcol">
		  <xh:td environment="newcol">$y = f(x)$:</xh:td><xh:td environment="newcol"><xh:strong environment="newcol">$\cap$</xh:strong></xh:td><xh:td environment="newcol"><xh:strong environment="newcol">$\cap$</xh:strong></xh:td><xh:td environment="newcol"><xh:strong environment="newcol">$\cup$</xh:strong></xh:td>
		</xh:tr>
		<xh:tr environment="newcol">
		  <xh:td environment="newcol">$f''(x)$:</xh:td>
		  <xh:td environment="newcol">$-$</xh:td><xh:td environment="newcol">$-$</xh:td><xh:td environment="newcol">$+$</xh:td>
		</xh:tr>
		<xh:tr environment="newcol">
		  <xh:td environment="newcol">$x$:</xh:td><xh:td environment="newcol">$(-\infty, 0)$</xh:td><xh:td environment="newcol">$(0, 6)$</xh:td><xh:td environment="newcol">$(6, \infty)$</xh:td>
		</xh:tr>
</xh:table>
It follows from this sign chart that $f$ is concave up on  $(6, \infty)$,
and concave down on $(-\infty, 0)$ and $(0, 6)$.
<xh:hr environment="newcol"/>
</collapse></newcol>
</xh:li>
<xh:li environment="statement">
Inflection points on the graph of $f$.
<newcol course="Math 1010" chapter="8" chapter_type="" section="3" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="newcol">
It follows from the sign chart for $f''$ that $(6, f(6)) = (6, 10/9)$
is the only reflection point on the graph of $f$.
<xh:hr environment="newcol"/>
</newcol>
</xh:li></xh:ol>
<xh:h5 xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" class="notkw" environment="statement">Graph</xh:h5>
<newcol course="Math 1010" chapter="8" chapter_type="" section="3" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="newcol">
<xh:div xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" class="image" environment="newcol">
<xh:iframe src="https://www.desmos.com/calculator/t5cgqvw7id?embed" width="500px" height="500px" style="border: 1px solid #ccc" frameborder="0" environment="newcol"/>
<xh:p environment="newcol"/><xh:br environment="newcol"/>
<xh:strong environment="newcol">
$
y = \dfrac{x^2 + x - 2}{x^2}
$
</xh:strong>
</xh:div>
</newcol>
</statement>
<xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" wbtag="newline" environment=""/>
